---
/**
 * context-engineering/0003 · Figure 3 — "The chunk-size trade-off"
 * (too big / too small / just right). Copied VERBATIM from the source lesson
 * (figure + svg + figcaption incl. footnote <sup>).
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 640 210"
        role="img"
        aria-label="A document split too big, too small, and just-right on function boundaries."
    >
        <!-- too big -->
        <text x="106" y="20" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#9a2417"
            >Too big</text
        >
        <rect x="36" y="30" width="140" height="120" rx="8" fill="#fbecec" stroke="#9a2417"></rect>
        <line x1="36" y1="90" x2="176" y2="90" stroke="#9a2417" stroke-dasharray="3 3"></line>
        <text x="106" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.2" fill="#6b675f"
            >diluted, averaged</text
        >
        <text x="106" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.2" fill="#6b675f"
            >embedding; imprecise</text
        >
        <text x="106" y="192" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.2" fill="#6b675f"
            >hits; wasted tokens</text
        >

        <!-- too small -->
        <text x="320" y="20" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#9a2417"
            >Too small</text
        >
        <rect x="250" y="30" width="140" height="120" rx="8" fill="#fbecec" stroke="#9a2417"></rect>
        <line x1="250" y1="54" x2="390" y2="54" stroke="#9a2417" stroke-dasharray="3 3"></line>
        <line x1="250" y1="78" x2="390" y2="78" stroke="#9a2417" stroke-dasharray="3 3"></line>
        <line x1="250" y1="102" x2="390" y2="102" stroke="#9a2417" stroke-dasharray="3 3"></line>
        <line x1="250" y1="126" x2="390" y2="126" stroke="#9a2417" stroke-dasharray="3 3"></line>
        <text x="320" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.2" fill="#6b675f"
            >lost surrounding</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.2" fill="#6b675f"
            >context; many</text
        >
        <text x="320" y="192" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.2" fill="#6b675f"
            >scattered fragments</text
        >

        <!-- just right -->
        <text x="534" y="20" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >Just right</text
        >
        <rect x="464" y="30" width="140" height="120" rx="8" fill="#e9f3ec" stroke="#2f5d3a"></rect>
        <line x1="464" y1="70" x2="604" y2="70" stroke="#2f5d3a"></line>
        <line x1="464" y1="110" x2="604" y2="110" stroke="#2f5d3a"></line>
        <text x="534" y="55" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#2f5d3a">fn calcTax()</text>
        <text x="534" y="95" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#2f5d3a">fn applyRule()</text>
        <text x="534" y="135" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#2f5d3a">fn format()</text>
        <text x="534" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.2" fill="#6b675f"
            >split on meaning</text
        >
        <text x="534" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.2" fill="#6b675f"
            >(function bounds);</text
        >
        <text x="534" y="192" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.2" fill="#6b675f"
            >each self-contained</text
        >
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        One chunk = one retrievable unit. Too big averages many ideas into one vague vector; too
        small strips the context that made a passage meaningful. <b
            >"Just right" splits on structure</b
        >, so each chunk is one coherent idea.<sup><a href="#s5" id="r5">5</a></sup>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
